   136→## How it works
   138→There's currently no native OTP/2FA/MFA input in HTML, which means people are either going with 1. a simple input design or 2. custom designs like this one.
   139→This library works by rendering an invisible input as a sibling of the slots, contained by a `relative`ly positioned parent (the container root called _OTPInput_).
   140→
   141→## Features
   143→This is the most complete OTP input on the web. It's fully featured 
   144→
   145→<details>
   146→<summary>Supports iOS + Android copy-paste-cut</summary>
   147→
   148→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bdbdc96a-23da-4e89-bff8-990e6a1c4c23
   149→
   150→</details>
   151→
   152→<details>
   153→<summary>Automatic OTP code retrieval from transport (e.g SMS)</summary>
   154→
   155→By default, this input uses `autocomplete='one-time-code'` and it works as it's a single input. 
   156→
   157→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/5705dac6-9159-443b-9c27-b52e93c60ea8
   158→
   159→</details>
   160→
   161→<details>
   162→<summary>Supports screen readers (a11y)</summary>
   163→
   164→Stripe was my first inspiration to build this library.
      →…
   198→### Auto tracks if the input has space in the right side for the badge
   200→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bf01af88-1f82-463e-adf4-54a737a92f59
   201→
   202→</details>
   203→
   204→## API Reference
   206→### OTPInput
   208→The root container. Define settings for the input via props. Then, use the `render` prop to create the slots.
   209→
   210→#### Props
   212→```ts
   213→type OTPInputProps = {
   214→  // The number of slots
   215→  maxLength: number
   216→
   217→  // Render function creating the slots
   218→  render: (props: RenderProps) => React.ReactElement
   219→  // PS: Render prop is mandatory, except in cases
   220→  // you'd like to consume the original Context API.
   221→  // (search for Context in this docs)
   222→
   223→  // The class name for the root container
   224→  containerClassName?: string
   225→
   226→  // Value state controlling the input
   227→  value?: string
   228→  // Setter for the controlled value (or callback for uncontrolled value)
   229→  onChange?: (newValue: string) => unknown
   230→
   231→  // Callback when the input is complete
   232→  onComplete?: (...args: any[]) => unknown
   233→
      →…
   293→## Examples
   298→```tsx
   299→export default function Page() {
   300→  const formRef = useRef<HTMLFormElement>(null)
   301→  const buttonRef = useRef<HTMLButtonElement>(null)
   302→
   303→  return (
   304→    <form ref={formRef}>
   305→      <OTPInput
   306→        // ... automatically submit the form
   307→        onComplete={() => formRef.current?.submit()}
   308→        // ... or focus the button like as you wish
   309→        onComplete={() => buttonRef.current?.focus()}
   310→      />
   311→
   312→      <button ref={buttonRef}>Submit</button>
   313→    </form>
   314→  )
   315→}
   316→```
   317→</details>
   318→
   319→<details>
